{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01XLid895XShuuKWEqR1BQPf","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The namespace itself is gone! The KARMA framework is managing the namespace lifecycle. The namespace got deleted and is being re-created. This is the KARMA framework re-running the scenario.\n\nLet me wait for the namespace to be re-created and then the RabbitMQ cluster to come back up. Looking at the original context, the scenario is `rabbitmq-failover-first-01` which involves a failover. The KARMA framework handles:\n1. Creating the namespace\n2. Deploying RabbitMQ\n3. Setting up the initial state (vhost /app, app-queue)\n4. Running the agent (me) to configure mirroring\n5. Injecting a failover/adversary\n6. Checking the oracle\n\nSo the sequence is: I configure mirroring first, then the framework injects the failover, then it validates the behavior.\n\nBut I'm noticing something odd about the version history. The initial cluster showed RabbitMQ 3.12.14, but after rabbitmq-0 was terminated and restarted, it came back as 4.1.8. That's a major version jump, which doesn't make sense unless the node was pulling a different image. Let me look more carefully at what the cluster_status output actually showed about the versions.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":492,"cache_read_input_tokens":48769,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":492},"output_tokens":17,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"360abd91-7e94-4194-a274-566f8aaa96ea","uuid":"4a75433b-6f66-4431-88ac-8cc759767d2d","request_id":"req_011CcdbvSm5rLN7J7NX4Bwxg"}
