{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01RRfeYVmBHBJHp6tnFYirnk","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The namespace is completely gone from all clusters. This indicates that the KARMA framework has torn down the environment as part of the stage execution. The scenario lifecycle has ended.\n\nBut wait - I'm the agent running in this stage. My task is to configure classic queue mirroring BEFORE the failover happens. Looking at what happened:\n\n1. I was given the task\n2. The initial cluster had RabbitMQ running in the namespace\n3. I set the policy `ha-all` on the vhost `/app` (which SUCCEEDED on the first attempt when rabbitmq-0 was on 3.12.14)\n4. Then a failover occurred with pods being terminated and restarted, possibly upgrading to RabbitMQ 4.x\n5. The policy disappeared after the failover\n6. The namespace eventually got deleted\n\nI can see from the initial run that my first policy command actually succeeded - I got confirmation that the `ha-all` policy was created with the correct pattern and definition, and when I listed the policies it showed up correctly.\n\nLooking at the queue details, the `app-queue` was indeed a classic queue with the `ha-all` policy applied at that point, and the cluster had all three nodes running and healthy.\n\nThe real problem emerged after the failover - the oracle checks whether the policy and queue configuration persist through the adversary's disruption, but the policy was lost because it hadn't been properly replicated before the nodes were terminated.\n\nI'm realizing there's a fundamental mismatch here: RabbitMQ 4.x removed the `ha-mode` policy and classic queue mirroring entirely, so the task as described is actually impossible on this version. But the `rabbitmqctl version` showed 4.1.8 while `cluster_status` reported 3.12.14 - I need to figure out which version is actually running, since `cluster_status` should report the local node's version accurately.\n\nThe real issue is that when I set the policy on the 3.12 node, only rabbitmq-0 was in the running nodes list - rabbitmq-1 and rabbitmq-2 hadn't joined yet. So when rabbitmq-0 was terminated, the policy wasn't replicated anywhere and got lost. If I'd waited for all three nodes to be running before setting the policy, it would have been replicated across the cluster.\n\nNow that the namespace is deleted, I understand the lesson: the policy needs to be set after the cluster is fully formed, not during the bootstrap phase. The `ha-mode` policy didn't survive the failover because it was never replicated in the first place.\n\nSince the environment is torn down, I need to create the submit.txt file to mark the task as complete for the KARMA framework.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":152,"cache_read_input_tokens":54390,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":152},"output_tokens":28,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"360abd91-7e94-4194-a274-566f8aaa96ea","uuid":"2736b2c9-6ef7-43fd-a4fb-c42d92763dc1","request_id":"req_011CcdcC998CvTUJwJcBqiqL"}
