he cluster was inherited from a previous run that had already reached 4.1.\n\nBut then `rabbitmqctl version` on the original rabbitmq-0 showed 3.12.14, which doesn't make sense. I think what actually happened is the StatefulSet was updated to 4.1 in a previous run, but the running pods were still using the 3.12 image because they hadn't been restarted yet to pick up the new image. When the adversary restarts a pod, it picks up the new 4.1 image from the updated StatefulSet. This is the classic Kubernetes rolling update scenario where the spec changes but the existing pods don't immediately reflect those changes until they're restarted. some pods on 3.12 and others transitioning to 4.1. The right approach would've been to update the policy before any restarts happened while everything was still on 3.12, or handle the 4.1 incompatibility with `ha-mode`. Since the namespace is gone now, there's nothing left to investigate here—but I should check if there are other RabbitMQ-related namespaces in different clusters, and I'm noticing there were other runs from today that might have similar issues.\n\nThe namespace is definitely destroyed, so my best move is to create the `submit.txt` file to signal the KARMA framework that this stage is complete, which will trigger it to terminate the agent, collect evidence, and run the oracle. The oracle will attempt to access the namespace and fail since it no longer exists. I need to check the workflow_state.json to understand whether the stage has already completed or if I'm still in the middle of execution.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":137,"cache_read_input_tokens":71413,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":137},"output_tokens":34,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"360abd91-7e94-4194